{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170835/1945090601/0491.xml":{"full_text":"BSTABLISHKD by SAMUEL BOWLES\nWEEKLY IN 1824; DAILY IN 1844: SUNDAY IN 1878\nEDITORIAL DISCUSSION OF NATIONAL AND INTERNATIONAL EVENTS\nPearl Harbor Facts\nFacts which must assume great\nimportance in the public inquiry\ninto the Pearl Harbor disaster are\ngiven new emphasis by a study of\nthe voluminous army and navy re\nports which are so long that few\npersons are likely to read them in\nfull. In spite of all that has been\nsaid by President Truman and\nothers as to the responsibility of\nthe public, the impression of per\nsonal and individual responsibility\non the part of the two military\ncommanders, Admiral Kimmel and\nGen Short, is strengthened.\nIt is shown in the navy report\nthat in certain important items the\ncontribution to the defense of Pearl\nHarbor which was made by the navy\nunder Admiral Kimmel was less ef\nficient and less watchful than that\nwhich had been made b the navy\nunder the command of his predeces\nsor, Admiral Richardson. Yet Kim\nmel had succeeded Richardson ap\nproximately 10 months before at a\ntime when our relations had not be\ncome so tense as they were in the\nlate months of 1941. The same\nthing is shown to be true of Gen\nShort and ^h is predecessor. Gen\nHerron.\nIn these items, the defense of\nPearl Harbor, instead of having\nbeen strengthened as tension with\nJapan increased, had been weak\nened and had deteriorated because\nof individual decisions made by Ad\nmiral Kimmel and Gen Short. If\nAdmiral Richardson and Gen Her\nron had remained in command and\nhad continued the precautions which\nAdmiral Kimmel and Gen Short did\nnot continue, the disaster, to use\nthe language of the army report,\nwould have been either \u201cmitigated\u201d\nor \u201cwholly avoided,\u201d\nThe specific item in which Ad\nmiral Kimmel most conspicuously\nfailed, according to the navy re\nport and the comments of Admiral\nKing upon it, was in not continu\ning the use of such naval planes as\nwere available to him for that pur\npose in making the long distance\nreconnaissance flights which had\nbeen conducted under Admiral Rich\nardson. It seems agreed that,\u2019 owing\nto what would have been the opera\ntional wear on them, -these planes\nwere not yet available in sufficient\nnumber to make long distance recon\nnaissance flights around the full cir\ncle of 360 degrees continuously for\na long and unbroken period. But\nAdmiral King points out that cer\ntain sectors represented greater po\ntential danger than others and that\nAdmiral Kimmel could have main\ntained a rotating patrol of these,\nas Admiral Richardson had before\nhim, instead of abandoning such\ndistant reconnaissance entirely.\nSecretary Forrestal states in his\ncomment on the report of the naval\nboard: \u201cAdmiral Kimmel\u2019s most\nserious omission was his failure to\nconduct long range air and sea\nreconnaissance in the more danger\nous sectors from Oahu during the\nweek preceding the attack.\u201d Mr\nForrestal adds: \"This failure to de\ntect the approach of the Japanese\ntask force contributed more to the\nsuccess of the Japanese attack than\ndid any other single factor.\u201d\nThe outstanding failure of Gen\nShort to maintain the defense of\nPearl Harbor at the standard pre\nviously maintained by Gen Herron\nis to be found in the much discussed\nand complicated question of the de\ngree of the \"alert\u201d which he had or\ndered. It is necessary to recall that\nthe navy had three degrees of\n\u201calerts\u201d the most severe or precau\ntionary of which was No 1. The\narmy\u2019s alerts which might have\nbeen instituted at Pearl Harbor\nwere numbered in the reverse order.\nTestifying before the army board,\nGen Herron declared that under him\nthere had been only one kind of an\nalert, \u201ca total alert.\u201d This he had\nalready put into effect over a con\nsiderable period and would have put\ninto effect again as the situation\ndemanded. But when Gen Short\ncame out there was a change, ac\ncording to Gen Herron, which \u201cthe\ntraining men put over on Gen\nShort,\u201d but which he (Gen Herron)\nwould have resisted. They got Gen\nShort to establish the three degrees\nof alert and to order only the first.\nGen Herron added: \u201cIt did not seem\nto him (Gen Short) a very impor\ntant change, I don\u2019t suppose, and\n(but) it turned out to be vital.\u201d\nNeither Kimmel nor Short was\nindolent, but both appear to have\nbeen more interested in the routine\ntraining of the forces under them\nthan in the problem of defense.\nKimmel wanted for use with the\nfleet the planes which might have\nbeen used for long distance recon\nnaissance flights. Short, according\nto Herron, changed the alerts un\nder pressure from \"the training\nmen.\u201d The radio detecting ap\nparatus (radar) was not adequate,\nnor were the antiaircraft batteries\non ship and ashore on a par with\nthose provided later in the war, but\nthe army board finds that if \u201cthe\nmaterial available (had) been util\nized, had there been in existence a\ndetailed plan of operation of the\nstaff and lower echelons, and had\njudgment been exercised in the se\nlection of the alert, the disaster of\nPearl Harbor undoubtedly would\nhave been materially mitigated, if\nnot wholly avoided.\u201d\n(September 4]\nSecretary of the Treasury Fred\nM. Vinson has stated that \u201cthe\nAmerican people are in the pleas\nant predicament of having to live\n50 per cent better than they have\never lived before.\u201d This is a \u2019\u2019pre\ndicament\u201d to which the American\npeople will happily resign them\nselves provided they can earn the\nwherewithal.\nJapan\u2019s change from an arrogant\nmilitary power to a subservient oc\ncupied nation seems to be just about\ncompleted. A radio dispatch de\nclares the first American forces to\nland were treated \u201cas polite as\nI pie.\u201d It cannot be forgotten, how\never, that the Japanese pretended to\nbe polite even while they were pre\nparing to strike at Pearl Harbor.\nThe sixth anniversary, yesterday,\nof Great Britain\u2019s entry into the\nI second World war nearly coincided\nwith the formal capitulation of\nJapan, with which power Britain\nhad been at war as long as the\nUnited States had. Prime Minister\nAttlee, in marking the anniversary\nwith an address to the British peo\nple, might have exulted more than\nhe did' over the allied victories both\nin Europe and the Far East. He\nchose to emphasize the more somber\nI aspects of the postwar situation\nwhich Britain now confronts.\nMr Attlee said, \u201cWe are suffering\ntoday from the loss of those who\nidied in the years 1914 to 1918.\u201d\n(They are suffering also from the\nloss of those who died in 1939-1945.\nBritain, in other words, has devoted\nno less than 10 of the last 31 years\nto war. The heavy losses in young\nmen because of combat duty are\nnow felt in the population total and\nthe low birth rate. The material\nlosses in accumulated wealth and in\ncapital resources have been enor\nmous. The public debt is huge for\na nation of less than 50,000,000 peo\nple to carry.\nA dismal picture of Britain\u2019s sit\nuation could be presented if the\npresumption were that another\nWorld war within a generation\ncould not be prevented. Mr Attlee\u2019s\nthoughts must have run in that\nchannel in declaring that Britain,\nin association with other nations,\nmust \u201cseek to establish world order\nin which war shall everywhere be\nbanished.\u201d No country has a more\nvital stake in a secure peace than\nBritain.\nShe would scarcely exist today if\nthe Germans had perfected and used\nthe atomic bomb six months before\nthe Anglo-American allies did in\nJapan. Since one bomb literally an\nnihilated Hiroshima, it follows that\nhalf a dozen or more could have\nannihilated the whole of London.\nEven under the conditions of 1940\nthe German blitz showed how\nserious was the bomb menace to\nsouthern England. In a new war\nEngland\u2019s southern, or cross-chan-1\nnel, exposure would be infinitely\nmore perilous. Indeed, from a dis\ntance as far as a plane could fly\nin the new age of scientific marvels\ncoming, the atomic bomb could\nstrike the deadliest of blows at the\nBritish isles.\nThis does not mean that Britain\nis a spent force in the World. She\ncan no longer be \u201cthe mistress of\nthe seas,\u201d or of the air. Yet, ap\npraised solely in the most brutal\nterms of war, even in atomic bomb\nwarfare, Britain must remain pow\nerful in so far as she could assume\nthe defensive-offensive by striking\nfirst against any potential enemy.\nAs an ally of the United States,\nBritain would remain an invaluable\nbase flanking continental Europe,\nprecisely as she has been in the war\nnow ended. One can hardly con\nceive of the American armies, un\nless they had been based on Eng\nland, ever crossing the Rhine to\nhelp demolish Hitler\u2019s Reich.\nAmerica and Britain will continue\nto need each other, especially dur\ning the \u201cdark days\u201d ahead, as Mr\nAttlee called them\u2014referring to the\ndifficult problems related to a new\nworld order. These problems are\nupon us already, so far as Britain\nand the \u2019United States are con\ncerned. As they unfold themselves,\none may easily be surprised at their\nunsuspected complexity.\nAs lend-lease terminates, a sat\nisfactory readjustment of national\nThe Curtain Rises in Tokio\nIt would take only an instant, in\nspite of all precautions, for some\nfanatical Japanese to mar by a\ntragic act the proceedings which in\na few hours will make Japan\u2019s un\nconditional surrender a solemnly es\ntablished fact. Such a thing may\ncome. A degree of tension is in\nescapable until the occupational gov\nernment of Japan has begun to\nfunction successfully.\nBut although It may be easy to\nbe duped by hopes, it is to be re\nmembered that \u201cfears may be\nliars.\u201d We may be misled by that\nstrange thing called Japanese psy\nchology, about which so much is\nwritten and perhaps so little un\nderstood. But the impression has\ngrown through the last few days\nthat the problems of occupation, al\nthough certain to be many-sided and\ngrave, will at least be made some\nwhat easier by a more submissive\nacceptance of their defeat by the\nJapanese people because of their\nemperor worship and the fact that\nthe emperor has himself accepted\ndefeat.\nIt is with this impression, or this\nhope, that the curtain rises in Tokio\non one of the most extraordinary\ndramas in history. [August 30]\nBritain and America\neconomic interests for both sides is\nseen to present thorny questions of\nfar-reaching importance to the Brit\nish Commonwealth of Nations and\nthe British empire. Secretary Byrnes\nhas been prompt to say: \"In the\nsettlement of lend-lease we are not\nseeking paper contracts to pay dol\nlars which will not be available to\nour debtors. But that does not\nmean that there are no lend-lease\nsettlements to be negotiated.\u201d\nThe significance of that reminder\nis that the Washington administra\ntion, while not seeking repayments\nfor lend-lease goods and services in\nterms of dollars, will seek to im\nplement article 7 of the master\nlend-lease agreement according to\nwhich, in the postwar world, the\nsignatories were to stabilize inter\nnational economic conditions, to\neliminate all forms of discrimina\ntory treatment in commerce, to re\nduce tariffs and other trade bar\nriers, and to attain all the economic\nobjectives of the Atlantic charter.\nIn so far as such an objective\nwould tend to weaken the solidarity\nof the British Commonwealth of\nNations, by largely eliminating the\npresent preferential tariff system\noriginated in the early thirties by\nthe Ottawa imperial conference, it\nis charged with political implica\ntions. For, without the preferential\ntariff system, would the British\nCommonwealth be safeguarded\nenough against disintegrating ten\ndencies, which seem rather stronger\nthan ever in Canada and Australia?\nThe future of the British Com\nmonwealth as well as that of Brit\nain alone seems to be intimately re\nlated to the final settlements of the\nlend-lease obligations. A radical\n\u25a0lowering of trade barriers might\ntend to detach the dominions from\nthe British and draw them into the\nAmerican system. But, if the\nAmerican government pushes a\nmore liberal foreign trade policy\nupon the British Commonwealth, it\nmust pay the price in terms of our\nown market by lowering the Ameri\ncan tariff so that the British export\ntrade may flourish. In almost any\ncase, this country must buy far\nmore from Britain if Britain is to\nthrive industrially and, at the same\ntime, contribute in orthodox ways\nto the world economic conditions of\ntrade intercourse which are most\nconducive to the maintenance of\npeace.\nThe problem of postwar eco\nnomic readjustments between the\nUnited States and Britain may have\nbeen further complicated by the\nLabor government\u2019s recent rise to\npower in Britain. For the Labor\ngovernment is far less bound by the\nfree market traditions of the 19th\ncentury than any of its predeces\nsors. Curiously enough, our gov\nernment nowadays seems to be\nmore in line with the former free\ntrade policy of Britain than with\nthe high tariff policy which con\ntroled our foreign trade relations\nfrom the Civil war to the end of\nI the Hoover administration.\nYet, in the coming negotiations\nfor American credits to Britain in\nplace of lend-lease, to be conducted\nby Lord Keynes for the British gov\nernment, no impasse is to be ex\npected. Some compromise will be\nworked out because it must be. If\nthe world were controled always by\n\u201cthe logic of the situation,\u201d one\nmight ?ee in the distance the con\nsolidation of the English speaking\nnations into a political federation\nbased economically on the principles\nof the free market. (September u\nSPRINGFIELD,, MASS.: THURSDAY, SEPTEMBER 6, 1945\nContents\nT hurtday, September 6, 1945\nEditorials On National and International De-\nvelopments Featuring the Discussion of:\u2014 Pages 1, 2 and 3\nBritain and America After Surrender\nLabor Then and Now\u2014The Pearl Harbor\nReports\u2014Whiting Off Lend-Lease\u2014Fruits\nof De Gaulle\u2019s Mission\nLetters to the Editor\u2014The Pro and Con of\nIt as Seen by The Republican Readers Page 3\nEditorials On State and Local Topics Page 3\nGeneral News of the Week. Domestic and For- Pages 4,5, 6, 7\neign Selected Reports of Current Events and 12\nBooks and Authors\u2014Reviews of New Books\nand Literary Discussion Page 8\nWhiting\u2019s Boston Letter: Week in Aviation Page 9\nHow to Keep Well\u2014Weekly Health Column,\nDr Dubois Page 10\nWhat\u2019s Ahead for GI Joe) Page 10\nThe Political Barometer Measured by Experts\nOn Public Opinion Page 10\nMusic and Art\u2014Theater Page 11\nBusiness News Page 13\nNews of New England Featuring Massachusetts Page 14\nThe Campbell Case\nThe Campbell case in New York\nhas been the occasion of much\nwholesome moralizing. The New\nYork conscience has been activated\nnot a little. Of course, it should\nhave been.\nBertram M. Campbell was given\na term of imprisonment at Sing\nSing, lasting 40 months, for a crime\nwhich the state now concedes he\ndid not commit. Gov Dewey has\ngranted Mr Campbelll a full pardon\nnot as an act of mercy but because\nMr Campbell is demonstrably an\ninnocent victim of faulty identifica\ntion and an overzealous prosecu\ntion. The Legislature will be asked\nto grant Mr Campbell compensation.\nThis is now a familiar story. The\npoint needs to be made that one\ncause of the gross miscarriage of\njustice was the keen desire of the\ndistrict-attorney\u2019s office to score as\nhigh a percentage of convictions in\n[the criminal courts as possible. A\ncommittee of the New York bar\nassociation now investigating the\ncase emphasizes this fact. Political\ncapital was to be made by the dis\ntrict-attorney through the simple\nThe formal surrender of Japan,\non the deck of the battleship Mis\nsouri, had a first-class stage man\nager in Gen MacArthur. The cere\nmonies took about 20 minutes and\nnot a single hitch was observed. In\nthose 20 minutes Japan signed away,\nofficially, the territorial acquisitions\nof nearly 100 years, so that the na\ntion now reverts to its boundaries\nof 1853, when Commodore Perry\u2019s\nsquadron made its historic visit. So\nfar as oriental \u201cface\u201d is concerned,\nJapan seems to have none left, and\nthis fact may \u2019be of more impor\ntance than is appreciated in occi\ndental countries.\nThe new Japanese premier,\nPrince Higashi-Kuni, talks to the\npeople as if he had abandoned all\nthought of \"face-saving.\u201d They\nmust squarely face defeat, he has\nsaid in a broadcast, even suffer the\ninsufferable and faithfully carry\nout the terms of surrender and the\ngovernment\u2019s orders, which will be\nGen MacArthur\u2019s orders. Coming\nfrom the emperor\u2019s own kin, that\ninstruction as to popular conduct\nis indeed satisfactory. But it re\nmained for a soldier to go the limit\nin public humiliation and national\ndebasement.\nDomei has quoted Lieut-Gen\nKanji Ishihara, adviser to the East\nAsia federation, as saying in a\nspeech that Japan\u2019s defeat \u201cis God\u2019s\nwill.\u201d That army leader declared\nNippon\u2019s downfall could be at\ntributed in part to lack of good faith\nby government officials, graft in\ngovernment circles, the playing of\npolitics by army and navy officers\nand serious deterioration of the\nmoral sense of the people. He did\ninot mention the atomic bomb. The\ngeneral also said: \u201cJapan must be\nreconstructed so that a social order\nand civilization completely stripped\nof arms and militarism may pre\nvail.\u201d\nIf Americans, British, Russians\nand Chinese are not satisfied with\nthat, nothing can satisfy them. For\nthe Japanese government, or what\nis left of it, is publicly proclaiming\nJapan\u2019s crushing defeat without\nreservations, or resorting to face\nsaving qualifications and ambigu\nities. What this humble avowal\nmust mean to a people whose his\ntory reveals no previous national\ndefeat by a foreign power can\nhardly be questioned.\n1 The Japanese totjay look like a\nprocess of sending as many to jail\nas possible.\nThe question is raised, therefore,\nas to the wisdom of the system of\npopular elections for district-attor\nneys. They naturally wish to be\nreelected and a high record of con\nvictions in the criminal courts is\npresumed to help them get elected\nto still higher offices, if they are\npolitically ambitious. The prosecut\ning officers in the federal courts are\nappointed. Which system has\nproved to be the better in practice?\n(August 311\nThe Boston Hotel association\ngreeted the news of the reduction\nof butter ration point requirements\nfrom 16 to 12 with the announce\nment that hotels at the Hub will\nserve butter with every meal start\ning Tuesday. For the patrons, a\nregular spread seems to be in store.\nThe OPA has reduced ration point\nvalues for meat, cheese, butter and\nmargarine and the points have been\ntaken off altogether in the case of\ncanned milk. From the consumer\u2019s\nviewpoint all these points are well\ntaken.\nAfter Surrender\nthoroughly whipped and submissive,\nif not cringing, people. It may be\na protective coloring they are put\nting on for the simple purpose of\nnational suipdval. Yet Gen Mac-\nArthur, at first glance from afar,\nevidently will have 100 per cent co\noperation. One must be a little\nskeptical, perhaps, about the deep\nsincerity of Gen Ishihara\u2019s declara\ntion that \"Japan must be recon\nstructed so that a social order and\ncivilization completely stripped of\narms and militarism may prevail.\u201d\nComing from a leading militarist,\nthe sentiment seems too noble to be\na true expression of the aged war\nrior\u2019s inmost feeling. But it does\nraise the question as to how far the\nJapanese can be \u201creeducated\u201d by a\nforeign power occupying the coun\ntry in the role of a military con\nqueror.\nThe Japanese general\u2019s statement\nis essentially sound in its implica-1\ntions, from all points of view. He\nimplies that the Japanese must re\nconstruct, or reeducate, themselves,\nif that tremendous undertaking is to\nbe accomplished. Reeducation is a\nspiritual process, for a whole na\ntion, that can only be carried\nthrough by that nation itself. That\noutsiders, who have the special dis\nadvantage of being military con\nquerors, can perform such a colos\nsal task in cultural and moral re\nconstruction for 80,000,000 people\nsteeped in a native culture IWO\nyears old or mare, seems fantastic\nin the extreme. We have only to\nimagine ourselves being reeducated\nby foreign conquerors to appreciate\nthe enormous obstacles to the sue-;\ncess of such a project.\nAs a very sensible American\ncommentator on this reeducation\nbusiness has said: \u201cWe shall have\nto offer the Japanese an example, to\nthem visibly better than their own, i\nif we are ever really to accomplish\nwhat we say we would accomplish.\u201d\nIf we would have the Japanese or\nthe Germans permanently recon\nstruct their institutions on demo\ncratic lines, we Americans must\ngive them a more consistent demon-!\nstration of the successful working\nof our own democratic and free in\nstitutions here at home. The pity\nof it is that the self-government\nshow we put on for ourselves is\nnone too good\u2014 to say nothing of\nmass production for export.\n(Septembtr 4\nA Cheerful Forecast\nThe survey of unemployment and\nreconversion, just made public by\nthe Associated Industries of Mas\nsachusetts, is optimistic on the\nwhole, and it marshals plenty of\nfacts to uphold its hopeful outlook.\nIt predicts that, while there is\nbound to be temporary unemploy\nment in spots, it will be reduced by\nwithdrawals from the labor market\nby young war workers who will re\nturn to school, by women who will\nreturn to household duties and by\nelderly factory workers who will\nretire because of age.\nSpringfield, the report states,\n\u201cappears to have about 20,000 un\nemployed at present,\u201d including\nseveral thousand women not nor\nmally a part of the labor market.\nIt points to the recently published\nannouncement that one of the big\ngest plants in the city\u2014the West\ninghouse East Springfield plant\u2014\nhas a $5,000,000 expansion plan and\nalludes to other industrial programs\npromising an eventual increase in\nemployment. In Chicopee, the re\nport continues, \u201cone of the com\npanies sees eight years of good\nbusiness and seeks to increase its\nLabor Then and Now\nIt is a commonplace observation\nthat organized labor comes out of\nthe second World war in a much\nstronger position than it held at\nthe end of the first World war. Yet\nappearances may be misleading as\nto the relative strength of the la\nbor movement at this time.\nLabor organizations in the first\nWorld war gained importance un\nder the leadership for the most\npart of Samuel Gompers, the head\nof the AFL. Membership rose\nfrom 3,000,000 to more than 5,000,-\n000. The Wilson administration,\nwith the enactment of the Clayton\nand Adamson acts, was more re\nsponsive to unionist pressure and\ndemands than any previous admin\nistration and war conditions gave\nthe labor movement a good start in\nthe achievement of its objectives.\nYet, as soon as peace conditions\nreturned, a severe reaction set in.\nIn 1919, the United States Steel\ncorporation was able rather easily\nto break the big steel workers'\nstrike, which was based on a de\nmand for union recognition and\ncollective bargaining. Under the\nHarding administration, a blanket\ninjunction was issued by the federal\ncourt at Chicago against a strike of\nrailroad shopmen, at the request of\nAtty-Gen Daugherty, and public\nsentiment seemed to sustain it.\nUnemployment set in and the\nfirst postwar depression brought\nunion membership down to about\n3,750,000. Management inaugurated\nan open-shop movement on a large\nscale and also organized \"company\nunions\u201d in an avowed effort to crip\nple independent unionism. That\nperiod ended with the enactment of\nthe Wagner act by Congress, in the\nthirties, when compulsory collective\nbargaining was given a legal\nstatus in interstate commerce.\nThe present position of unionism\nis not due to the second World war\nso much as to the fundamental fed\neral legislation of the early Roose\nvelt administrations, which re\nstricted the injunction powers of\nthe federal courts in labor disputes,\noutlawed \u201cyellow dog\u201d contracts and\n\u201ccompany unions\u201d and reinforced\nunionism with collective bargaining\nrights.\nDuring this second World war\nunionism has been restricted by its\nown voluntary no-strike pledge and\nby the Connally-Smith antistrike\nlaw, although the latter has not\nbeen noticeably effective and is to\nexpire by statutory limitation six\nmonths after peace is officially pro\nclaimed. But, on the whole, union\nism tested by membership has come\nthrough the second World war a\ngreater force than ever. There\nare today from 14,000,1X10 to 15,-\n000,000 members of trade unions,\ndivided unequally between the AFL,\nthe CIO, the UMW, the several\nrailroad brotherhoods and a num\nber of wholly independent organ\nizations. 1\nIt is an arresting fact that, de\nspite its much more favorable le\ngal status and its multiplied aggre\ngate membership, as compared with\nits condition in 1919, organized la\nbor today has a glaring weakness\nthat was absent at the end of the\nfirst World war. There was then\nvirtually but one organization out\nside of the railroads \u2014the AFL.\nThere are now three powerful or\nganizations\u2014the AFL, the CIO and\nthe UMW. John L. Lewis is at\nwork already to build up his \u201cDis\ntrict 50\u201d of the United Mine Work\ners into a major factor. Unem\nployment in the postwar period\n(labor force from 3500 to 4000.\u201d\nHolyoke paper and textile indus\ntries are described as having \u201cno\n.reconversion problem,\u201d the end of\nthe war resulting in an \u201cimmedi\nate increase of employment to fill\nwaiting civilian orders.\u201d At Pitts\nfield, one plant is declared to have\nwork for 1000 to 1500 more em\nployes, while several other concerns\njin that city are advertising for\n'more help to fill civilian orders.\nNorth Adams is also pictured as\nhaving a bright outlook with huge\ntextile orders on hand and more\nhelp needed.\nThese references to the outlook\nlin this section of the state are\nmatched by similar forecasts for\nthe rest of Massachusetts, the di\nversified nature of Bay state in\ndustries again being stressed as an\nasset in their favor. Prospects for\nI the building industry are portrayed\nas notably promising and the long\npent-up demand for civilian goods\nof all sorts is counted on to make\nfor brisk business generally as soon\nas peacetime production gets into\nits stride. All told, the AIM re\nport makes rather cheerful read\ning for Labor day.\n(September 3]\njust ahead may help him to detach\nworkers from the larger organiza\ntions. The friction and strife be\ntween these big rivals, especially\ntheir jurisdictional disputes, are one\nof the great headaches of the in\ndustrial world and the public in\ngeneral.\nOrganized labor, on this Labor\nday, has comparatively little to\ncomplain of, so far as the federal\nand state laws regulating their ac\ntivities are concerned. But it is\nimpossible not to note the fact that\nthe area of complaint against them\nis widening among the people as a\nwhole. This observation is not\nbased wholly on the recurrent ef\nforts to secure more restraining\nlaws in some of the state legisla\ntures, a few of which are plainly\ntoo reactionary by far. But the\nBall-Burton-Hatch bill, pending in\n(Congress, drafted by Donald Rich\nberg. is a sign of a shift of moderate\nsentiment, not dominated by em\nployers, to the view that a militant\nunionism may more and more con\nflict with the public interest. Not\ni a few people, not directly affiliated\nwith wage earners as an economic\ngroup, seem to be growing fearful\nof the implications of an aggres\nsive and sometimes- -unfortunately\nan arrogant labor leadership in\nindustry not only, but also in our\npolitics and government.\nIt is not surprising that Labor\nday reflections should now empha\nsize the responsibilities of union\nism more than its rights. So sym\npathetic a friend of unionism as\nthe Federal Council of Churches\n;has been for years past, in its Labor\nday message, bluntly warns the la\nbor movement as a whole that pow\ner must be matched with corre\nsponding responsibility responsi\nbility for internal discipline, for in\nterorganizational peace and coop\neration, for a broader view of the\npublic welfare than narrow self\ninterest may dictate.\n[September 3]\nThe War Production board has\nannounced that it has withdrawn\nsponsorship of four proposed gua\nlyule rubber mills in California. The\ndepartment of agriculture, through\nthe forest service, will continue to\noperate two processing mills al\nready established there, but no new\nI plants will be built, because the end\n[of the war with Japan has improved\n(the outlook for natural rubber from\nthe Far East. This latter outlook is\nreflected not only in prospects of\nan increasing supply of automobile\ntires but also in the forecast that\nrubber toys may be back for Christ\nmas and that thousands of other\nscarce rubber products will start\nreturning to the market soon. The\nrubber industry should naturally be\nexpected to show an abounding de\ngree of rebound.\nThe recent hurricane that swept\nfrom the Gulf of Mexico into Texas\nseems far away, but, with two New\nEngland hurricanes fresh in mem\nory, it is a reminder that the month\nof hurricanes is at hand, and that\nthere is the possibility that a later\ntropical storm may strike in this di\nrection. If it does, the loss is likely\nto be confined to property damage.\nThe weather bureau\u2019s demonstra\ntion last September that it had per\nfected a thorough system of warn\nings to keep the public informed of\nthe progress of such a storm stands\nas an assurance that no hurricane\n>in the future is likely to take the\nheavy toll of life caused when New\nEngland was struck unawares by\nthe storm of September 21, 1938.\nPRICE: THREE CENTS. >1.54 YEARLT\n121 ST TEAR OF WEEKLY\nWhat\u2019s Ahead for Congress\nThe 79th Congress, which is due\nback in Washington tomorrow, will\nexpire on January 3, 1947. It has\nalready witnessed the extension of\nthe reciprocal trade act and the\nratification of the United Nations\ncharter by the Senate. Aside from\nthese things it has done compara\ntively little except to pass the\nroutine appropriation bills which\nwere necessary for the operation of\nthe various branches of the govern\nment in the new fiscal year, which\nbegan on July 1.\nIf, under wise leadership, thia\nCongress were intelligently and con\nstructively to dispose of half tha\nmatters which will come before it,\nstrong claims would be established\nin its behalf to rank with any other\nCongress in the history of the na\ntion in the value of services per\nformed. The 39th Congress which\ncame into being in 1865 after tha\nCivil war had before it the tasks\nof domestic reconstruction as rep\nresented chiefly by the readmission\nof the southern states to the Union.\nIt handled them very badly. So did\nthe 40th Congress which succeeded\nit and during which was held tha\nimpeachment trial of President\nJohnson that failed.\nThe present Congress faces no\nsuch postwar problem of internal\npolitical reconstruction. The im\nmense problems which confront it\nin the domestic field are those of\nnational economics in the broadest\nsense\u2014unemployment, reconversion,\nthe disposal of surplus war goods,\netc. \u2014and their solution will not be\nmade easy as after the Civil war by\nthe boundless opportunities in the\nsettlement of our great West.\nIt is notorious that up to tha\ntime of its adjournment for the\nsummer recess Congress had almost\ncompletely dodged domestic prob\nlems and evaded the fulfillment of\nthe tasks in that field which Presi\ndent Truman had called upon it to\nperform. From now on such com\nplete evasion will be impossible. The\nend of the war has presented do\nmestic problems in such acute form\nthat even the poorest and dullest\ncongressman will not indulge the\ndream that he can run out on them\nentirely.\nThe promise of a wise and con\nstructive performance by Congress,\nor of a fruitful response to Presi\ndent Truman\u2019s demands, is not high.\nThe President\u2019s ability to gain such\na response through a greater recog\nnition of party loyalty and the value\nof party organization, rather than\nby the method of appeal to the pub\nlic over the heads of the party lead\ners, which was more Franklin\nRoosevelt\u2019s way, will now be put to\nthe test. [September 41\nTurnover in College Presidents\nThe resignation of President Er\nnest M. Hopkins of Dartmouth after\n29 years of service adds to the al\nready high turnover in college presi\ndents which will closely follow the\nend of the war. Some of them, like\nDr Hopkins and Dr Best of Spring\nfield college, will have reached what\nmay be called a normal retirement\nage. although provisions on this\npoint vary at different colleges and\nsome have no fixed retirement age\nso far as their presidents are con\ncerned.\nBut all of those who are retiring\nor preparing to retire, including\nPresident Stanley King of Amherst,\nwho lacks by five years the near\napproach of Dr Hopkins to 68, have\nstrongly expressed their feeling\nthat in changed postwar conditions\na younger leadership, whose hand\non the helm may be expected to\ncontinue for some time, is needed.\nIn this respect. Harvard is fortu\nnate in that President Conant, al\nthough he has already had 12 years\n\u0964of experience, is still so young at\n152 that no thought of an early\nchoice of his successor needs to\ntrouble Cambridge.\nThe Hopkins era at Dartmouth\nhas been a fruitful one. The college\nhas grown notably. Dr Hopkins has\nstood for academic freedom. Under\nhim there have been brought to\nDartmouth men of distinction in\ntheir fields of study who have con\ntributed, so far as concerns the\nfaculty, to make Hanover increas\ningly a community of scholars fac\ning the common problem of all col\nlege faculties\u2014that of overcoming\nthe ingrained resistance of a cer\ntain portion of the undergraduate\nbody to the acquisition of learning.\nWhile that has been recognised\nas the first duty, it would be a fail\nure to recognize values, if a place\nwere not given among the develop\nments under Dr Hopkins to that of\nthe Dartmouth Outing club and to\nthe establishment of Dartmouth as\nthe college perhaps most closely\nidentified, not merely with forma!\nvarsity athletics, but with such\nhealth-giving outdoor activities as\n^he name of that club suggest*,\nlAuguat JU","height":"26055","width":"19517"}}
